<subsection xml:id="sec-gerrymandering">
    <title>Gerrymandering</title>

    <sidebyside>
        <!-- <sbsrow> -->
            <!-- <sbspan> -->
                <p>
                     The process of dividing the state into the appropriate number of 
					 districts is called <em>redistricting</em>, but in the popular press,
					 it is often referred to as <em>gerrymandering</em>. This is because 
					 the map-makers often decide to split things up to their benefit. 
					 One of the earliest, most obvious examples of this was in 1812 
					 when Massachusetts Governor Gerry and his party drew one district
					 in such a curvy and jagged manner that the local press thought it looked
					 like a salamander (see Figure <xref ref="fig-gerrymander" />) and 
					 coined the term <em>Gerrymander</em>.
                </p>
            <!-- </sbspan> -->
            <!-- <sbspan> -->
                <figure xml:id="fig-gerrymander">
					<caption>An early example of a gerrymandered district, resembling a salamander.</caption>
                    <image source="gerrymandering.png"/>
                </figure>
            <!-- </sbspan> -->
        <!-- </sbsrow> -->
    </sidebyside>

