    <p>
        The last diagram is an example of the ‘packing’ and ‘cracking’ 
         that are illustrative of modern gerrymandering
    </p>
    <p>
         <m>\textbf{ packing}</m> Putting a very large number of voters who all vote the same way 
         in a single district. In this case, the election is won by these voters, 
         but by a very large margin.
    </p>
    <p>
         <m>\textbf{cracking}</m> Putting a slight majority of voters for one party in a single
         district. In this case, the election is won by these voters by a slim margin. 
         There are a lot of minority voters in the district, but not enough
         to ever win an election.
    </p>
